beastlords dutifully back their's off<br>
shadow knights dutifully back their's off<br>
druids dutifully back their's off<br>
main tank and assist tanks back off<br>
mob either ignores gimpy wizard/cleric pets or promptly EATS them in 1 tick<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->The problem is that this doesn't always happen.  Not saying that it's always clerics and wizards but here is the problem, two actually:<br>
<br>
Mages, and to a similar extent Necros, tend to be always watching their pets, even if it sometimes hurts their contribution otherwise.  Mages especially can generally afford to take a few seconds break from nuking to watch where their pet is.  Healers may be distracted by something far more important, like someone needing a heal.  Heals generally can't wait.  SKs and Beastlords who are in the thick of combat often find their pets behind them and impossible to see.  Enchanters generally aren't a problem except that I've met a fairly large number of enchanters who are simply inexperienced at controlling pets in a raid situation.  <br>
<br>
The second problem is the lack of pet hold.  If the mob has an AE, backing off a pet with anything other than pet hold will only last until the next AE hits.  If there are 4-5 people without pet discipline that all make little mistakes like this, it adds up quickly and you can lose 5-6 seconds of critical movement.<br>
<br>
Once you add the problems non-mages have backing off pets, and the possibility of any one person slacking(mage or otherwise) that nice process you have listed doesn't usually happen.  Eventually you'll get all the pets off, but until you do those hammers and swords will be beating on the mob pushing it wherever you don't want it to go, whether into adds, out of healing range, etc..<br>
<br>
It's always good take responsibility and call your pet off in an instant, not depend on others to do their job right.  Of course, invising the clerics to kill pets would likely be more trouble than it's worth.<br>
<br>
